# Review of `app.js` — Error Handling, Input Validation & Security

The file is a minimal Express server (22 lines, two routes). Here are concrete improvements, ordered by impact.

## 1. Missing error-handling middleware
Express swallows async/sync errors unless you register a 4-argument error handler. Currently, any thrown error would leak stack traces via the default handler in development mode.

```js
// After all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // send to a real logger (winston/pino), not stdout
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});

// 404 fallthrough
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' }));
```

## 2. `app.listen` has no error handler
If the port is in use, the process crashes with an uncaught exception.

```js
const server = app.listen(3000, () => { /* ... */ });
server.on('error', (err) => {
  console.error('Failed to start server:', err);
  process.exit(1);
});
process.on('unhandledRejection', (err) => { console.error(err); process.exit(1); });
process.on('uncaughtException',  (err) => { console.error(err); process.exit(1); });
```

## 3. No security headers
Add `helmet` to set sensible defaults (CSP, X-Frame-Options, HSTS, etc.):

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
app.disable('x-powered-by'); // helmet does this, but good to be explicit
```

## 4. No rate limiting
Both `/health` and `/users` are unauthenticated and trivially DoS-able.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100, standardHeaders: true }));
```

## 5. No body parser limits (in case POST routes are added)
When you add write endpoints, cap the payload size to prevent memory-exhaustion:

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

## 6. No input validation on future routes
Neither current route accepts input, but the pattern to adopt is schema validation — never trust `req.params`, `req.query`, or `req.body`. Use `zod` or `joi`:

```js
const { z } = require('zod');
const UserIdParams = z.object({ id: z.coerce.number().int().positive() });

app.get('/users/:id', (req, res, next) => {
  const parsed = UserIdParams.safeParse(req.params);
  if (!parsed.success) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid id' });
  // ... use parsed.data.id
});
```

This prevents NoSQL/SQL injection via coerced types, prototype-pollution payloads, and path-traversal strings.

## 7. PII leakage in `/users`
Returning `email` on an unauthenticated endpoint is a data-exposure issue. Either:
- require authentication (e.g., JWT middleware), or
- return only non-sensitive fields (`id`, `name`) from public endpoints.

## 8. Hardcoded port & no environment config
Move config to env vars and fail fast if required vars are missing:

```js
const PORT = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
if (!Number.isInteger(PORT) || PORT < 1 || PORT > 65535) {
  throw new Error(`Invalid PORT: ${process.env.PORT}`);
}
```

## 9. No CORS policy
If any browser client will call this API, add an explicit allowlist rather than the permissive default:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example.com'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

## 10. Logging
`console.log` isn't structured and has no request correlation. Use `pino-http` or `morgan` for access logs and a real logger for app logs — and scrub secrets/PII before logging.

