# Review of `app.js` — Error Handling & Input Validation

The file is small (22 lines), which makes the gaps easy to enumerate. Here are concrete issues and suggested improvements, grounded in specific lines.

## Issues Identified

### 1. No global error handler (all routes)
Express swallows errors silently without a 4-arg middleware. Any thrown error or rejected promise inside a handler will leak a stack trace in dev or hang the request in prod.

**Fix:** Add an error-handling middleware at the end of the middleware chain:
```js
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err); // log internally, never echo to client
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});
```

### 2. No `404` / unknown-route handler
Unmatched routes fall through to Express's default HTML response, which leaks framework info.
```js
app.use((req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' }));
```

### 3. Missing security headers (lines 4–5)
No `helmet` middleware is registered. This leaves the app without CSP, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, etc.
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 4. No body-parsing limits
If you later add `app.use(express.json())`, set a size cap to prevent memory-exhaustion DoS:
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
```

### 5. No rate limiting
`/users` and `/health` are trivially scrapeable/abusable. Add `express-rate-limit`:
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));
```

### 6. `/users` leaks PII unconditionally (lines 11–16)
Email addresses are returned with no authentication. Even for mock data, this pattern tends to get copied. Gate the route behind auth middleware and consider scoping fields:
```js
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  res.json(users.map(({ id, name }) => ({ id, name })));
});
```

### 7. No input validation scaffolding
Neither route currently takes input, but there is no validation library wired up for when they will. Adopt `zod` or `express-validator` now so future routes validate by default. Example for a future `/users/:id`:
```js
import { z } from 'zod';
const IdSchema = z.coerce.number().int().positive();

app.get('/users/:id', (req, res, next) => {
  const parsed = IdSchema.safeParse(req.params.id);
  if (!parsed.success) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid id' });
  // ...
});
```

### 8. `app.listen` has no error handling (line 18)
If port 3000 is in use, the process crashes with an unhelpful `EADDRINUSE`. Capture it:
```js
const server = app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server running on port 3000'));
server.on('error', (err) => { console.error('Listen failed:', err); process.exit(1); });
```

### 9. No `process`-level safety nets
Add handlers so unhandled rejections don't leave the server in an undefined state:
```js
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => { console.error(reason); process.exit(1); });
process.on('uncaughtException',  (err)    => { console.error(err);    process.exit(1); });
```

### 10. Hard-coded port / no config validation
Line 18 hard-codes `3000`. Read from `process.env.PORT` and validate it's a positive integer before binding.

### 11. Response of `/health` leaks server time (line 8)
Minor, but `timestamp` can aid fingerprinting. If the endpoint is public, consider returning just `{ status: 'ok' }`; keep the timestamp for an internal/authenticated `/health/detailed`.

### 12. No `trust proxy` setting
If deployed behind a load balancer, `req.ip` will be wrong, defeating rate limiting. Add `app.set('trust proxy', 1);` when applicable.

## Suggested Rewrite (consolidated)

```js
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const app = express();
const PORT = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;
if (!Number.isInteger(PORT) || PORT <= 0) throw new Error('Invalid PORT');

app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));

app.get('/health', (_req, res) => res.json({ status: 'ok' }));

app.get('/users', (_req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob' },
  ]);
});

app.use((_req, res) => res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' }));
app.use((err, _req, res, _next) => {
  console.error(err);
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});

const server = app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
server.on('error', (err) => { console.error(err); process.exit(1); });

process.on('unhandledRejection', (r) => { console.error(r); process.exit(1); });
process.on('uncaughtException',  (e) => { console.error(e); process.exit(1); });

module.exports = app;
```

